commits.commitMessage:
Improve argument parsing in configTest

Previously, the code would dereference a NULL pointer if an argument was
not provided to configTestD.

Resolves: LE-16481
Change-Id: I9442b00b7f35c6a003a5b50e8c8ab559ce4a28d2
commits.subject: Improve argument parsing in configTest

commits.commitMessage:
Allow multiple creation of the same sensor

When someone accidentally creates the exact same Input or Output
more than once, log a warning, instead of aborting, to make things
a little more robust.

Resolves: LE-16481
Change-Id: Iff7bde595c467f77a10e2502853d2261e8d9501b
commits.subject: Allow multiple creation of the same sensor

commits.commitMessage:
Call Admin API Push handler on registration

Make the Admin API push handlers behave consistently with
the I/O API push handlers by having them called when registered
if the resource has a value already.

Resolves: LE-16481
Change-Id: I5d14b15b7ebed122786a0baca4cf326c65d93e08
commits.subject: Call Admin API Push handler on registration

comments.message: This will be a breaking change for Octave.  I am reviewing the use of admin_Add*PushHandler in Octave and will open an Octave ticket to deal with the change.
Ticket is open for Octave to adapt to new admin API behavior before sync-ing with the datahub BROOKLYN-4752

commits.commitMessage:
Minor doc improvements

- Disabled the tree view because it's broken when served
  by a web server.
- removed mention of sdirTool.c which isn't part of this project.
- Removed the .api files from the list of files parsed by Doxygen.
- Force extraction of info from .h files generated by ifgen that
  are missing the @file directive.

Resolves: LE-16481
Change-Id: Iac856f888d34bf7ffe5f4db167e6b460afd5a58d

commits.commitMessage:
Refactor io.api to allow easier overriding of parameter sizes

Refactor io.api to include an ioDefs.api which defines the size of
parameters which can be adjusted according to the capabilites of the
platform.  To select the API sizes to use, add either the linux/ or
rtos/ directory to the interface search path, as appropriate.

Also move all APIs into an interfaces/ directory to conform to best
practices.

Resolves: LE-16328
Change-Id: I6feb490fb024cc18aa321d1ea83d13206810e31e
commits.subject: Refactor io.api to allow easier overriding of parameter sizes

commits.commitMessage:
Enable Periodic Sensor to utilize DataHub Admin API

The periodic sensor component has, up until now, relied exclusively
on the dataHub IO API for creating and managing the sensor data resources.
However, with recent changes to align the Admin API with the IO API,
clients, such as the periodic sensor, are now able to create
periodic sensor resouces using either absolute or relative resource
paths.

These changes:

1) Enable the periodic sensor component to use the Admin API
or the IO API to create either absolute or relative resource paths,
respectively.

2) A new build flag, MK_CONFIG_PERIODIC_SENSOR_ABSOLUTE, has been added
to determine which API (Admin or IO) is used that utilizes interface
alias names.

Resolves: LE-16241
Change-Id: I5a0a271744cbbc46a6ec660cb1a4a3142b49d933
commits.subject: Enable Periodic Sensor to utilize DataHub Admin API

Looks good.  Just a couple of minor comments - one change required.
Thanks,
Ian

Just remembered that PSENSOR_MAX_NAME_BYTES needs to be shorter than IO_MAX_RESOURCE_PATH_LEN by strlen("trigger").  The periodic sensor module appends "value", "enable", "period", and "trigger" to the path which is passed in

That doesn't appear to be part of this topic, has it already been merged?

Allow to escape all characters of a Json string

  If we had a string equal to "string\\", an issue occurred. the last
  quote was considered as escaped. now we allow to escape all characters.

Change-Id: I724d7371dd65faf6d57937e9b097086f2022b61e
Signed-off-by: ogallais <OGallais@sierrawireless.com>

commits.commitMessage:
Add Configuration Parser Implementation

    - Add the new config.api file that provides Load and Destination
      Push handler features.
    - Add parser component, a standalone component that parsers
      the (octave) json file.
    - Add new tests for the config.api feature.
    - Add destination field to each observation and the API to
      register push handler for a specific destination.
    - Remove extra sample allocation in push(data sample copy)

Resolves: LE-15993 LE-16003 LE-15988 LE-16004
Change-Id: I1f9a9a20e8db4a8a2385a654c8ae0144993c603a
commits.subject: Add Configuration Parser Implementation

comments.message: Should this be inside the Octave enabled block?  Similarly below.

hmmm, that's good question. we didn't think about.
nothing is stopping a regular non octave client to use the same json format and pass in config file.
but we also have not specified the schema in the datahub documentation.

what do other people think?

I think noticed that putting this component in the octave enabled block will essentially mean that the config.api is also only provided when octave is enabled.

Is that something we want?
It's a good question.   If we moved this into an Octave-only enabled block, then we would probably have to also move the configService files and config.api into this as well.

I would think the config.api would stay visible, but would only return LE_NOT_SUPPORTED or similar if there were no applicable back-ends available.  The encoding type is passed as a parameter, so it's easy to detect if it is not supported.  I do a similar thing for the back-ends of the snapshot API.

Seems like Jon thinks the JSON schema should be owned by datahub now.
In that case, then the name octaveParser has to change.
Not really necessary.  This will be put in the BSS and zeroed out if you don't provide an initializer.
Don't put the NULL check for this pointer in the while loop.  It only needs to be evaluated once.
This seems icky to me.  Is there no better way to do this?  Have a visited flag on each observation?  Maybe use the existing relevance flag?

Do you mean the whole idea of having a visited list or having to use dynamic vs static for different platforms?

I like the idea of a visited flag, saves some stack and there's no need for platform checks.
It adds an extra traversal at the end because flags need to be cleared.
We could just flip the flag from one to zero and zero to one and not have to clear them but that's more complexity. I'd assume one more traversal isn't that costly for this rarely used algorithm.

I was just thinking to use the existing relevance flag, since it's purpose is to indicate relevance of the resource to the current operation.  I use it in the snapshot API, but that would never be executing at the same time as this.  In that case, I do a traversal to set the flag and then clear it during the second pass.

It means the time complexity goes from N to 2N, but it's not like the number of resources is actually very big, even on a "large" Linux-based module.

I see. the reason I thought using a new flag would be better is that I didn't want to interfere with other operations or let other operation interfere with this one. but if relevance flag is intended for this particular purpose then it's ok.
I'll make the change.
As a caveat, using seek means that this API cannot be used over RPC, currently (not the that we need to in the scenario that motivated this change).

so we need to mention that in the API doc?
I know RPC doesn't support seeking on file descriptors but the input to the Load function is actually the file path not the file descriptor. for RPC, the file path is just a string.
so if remote clients want to use the Load function they have to figure out a way of transferring the file themselves?
Yes, I think just a note in the documentation to say that this is restricted to IPC use is fine.

that would work,
what about something like this though:

If used over rpc, the file path must be local to the server.
Yes, I think this comment explains it and makes it clear.
Still not sure why this is a URL as opposed to just a file path.

I'd like a file path more than URL too.
I think Jon's idea was to support file stream and online files too. but we have to download those into a local file anyway, which we can ask the client to do.
Yeah, that was more a general comment, not really an issue with the code review.

I've already made the switch to file path instead of url.
will ask for more feedback in the next patchset.
Double colon?  Shouldn't it be one?
I think this is a private function.  We should rename it to configService_TriggerDestinationPushHandler() instead.
It would be preferable to use snprintf here, as it is less prone to incorrect usage.
Don't use strcat.  If necessary, strncat, but better yet would be to combine these two calls into one snprintf call.
Can we not just use the word "Observations?"
Should we remove this if we are no longer using it to initialize variables/data on start up?
Ditto - remove this if we do not require it.

This is the wrong size.  It should be srcPathSize - strlen(srcPath).  I had actually been thinking to use a local buffer in resTree_GetPath() and then just have a call like

    snprintf(srcPath, srcPathSize, "%s/%s", buf, jsonExtraction);
What are the values that can be put here?  Can I make up any random string or are there specific strings I have to use?

well today it has to be "json"
anything else will return LE_UNSUPPORTED.
Should include config.api here as well.
Could just be a strncpy in this case, but it's not a big deal.

comments.message:
Hmm...  JSON actually allows any unicode code point from 0020 to 10FFFF, with the exception of double quotes (") and reverse solidus (\), unless they are escaped.

https://www.json.org/json-en.html

We may wish to restrict that further to prevent issues with client code, but it may be considered intolerant of users that prefer different languages than English. Currently, no Octave official release uses other characters, but mangOH users could if this supported that. Mind you, there are no tests for that, so there may be issues elsewhere in the technology stack too.

commits.commitMessage:
Remove Datahub PlaceholderPool

    Remove the placeholder pool from resource.c. Instead Add mechanism
to allocate an IO or Observation as placeholder whenever a path that is
not yet created is being used.

Resolves: LE-15876
Change-Id: I9c945feadd59149dca1003352579ef6198059974
commits.subject: Remove Datahub PlaceholderPool

comments.message: Reviewed.  Waiting for the next patch to address Jen's comments
I don't understand why resRef needs to be checked if res is being checked, and I especially don't see why resRef would ever be checked before res.

I think it would be more efficient to keep a static pointer to this namespace entry.

Also, I wonder if we should even just eliminate the Root entry and have two roots, one for the /obs/ tree and one for the /app tree?  Then we can have something like this:

 entryRef = resTree_FindObservation(path)
 entryRef = resTree_CreateObservation(path)

 entryRef = resTree_FindIO(path)
 entryRef = resTree_CreateIO(path)

Then the caller can set the properties on the entry, including the entry type. The default would be a Placeholder with a Trigger data type.

you mean more efficient in performance ?
we've been doing this so far and I think keeping it the same it a better idea.
This should never be called if something already exists at that location.
Should never be called for a path that already has a resource.

Placeholders should not have JSON examples. But, this would be an internal bug if it had one, because it should get removed when the I/O object gets converted to a Placeholder. We could remove this and add it to the automated tests instead.

Hmm... This doesn't seem correct. The JSON example should get added when the data source of the resource is set to something that has a JSON example, and it should get removed when the data source is changed to something else or the resource is deleted.

My intuition tells me that placeholders should not propagate samples and conversion to a placeholder should cause any current value to be deleted, regardless of its type. If we are going to do that, the check for whether a current value exists should be based on resPtr->currentValue, not based on resPtr->currentType.

yes, I think the fact that today, values of triggers were not being released was simply because the default currentType for a placeholder was TRIGGER and the res_MoveAdminSettings function wasn't releasing currentValue if currentType was equal.
I don't see the need for a warning here.

Seems to me that resTree_GetObservation() shouldn't require the caller to look up the /obs namespace entry first. It doesn't make any sense to get an observation from anywhere else, and the resource tree is the keeper of the namespace entry anyway.

Also, I would prefer to see resTree_GetObservation() split into resTree_FindObservation() (or resTree_FindEntry()) and resTree_CreateObservation(), as we did for other things in past changes.
I believe that's outside the scope of this ticket. This minor change is exactly replicating the current code.
If we don't clean as we go, the mess will build up.  If you want to defer a change, please create a ticket for that, so at least the technical debt is tracked.
I agree, please create a ticket.
Would prefer to see resTree_FindObservation() here.
as noted in another comment, will create ticket for the change.
This parameter doesn't seem to be needed.
This parameter doesn't seem to be needed.
I've changed the resTree_GetResource to do that.

No. For one thing, there's no such return code as LE_NO_PARAMETER. Also, this description of the behaviour of resTree_GetResource() doesn't match the documentation for resTree_GetResourrce() above, and as far as I can tell, the code matches the function's documentation, not this comment.
Documentation of resTree_GetResourrce says: "If there's already a Namespace at the given path, it will be replaced by a Placeholder".
I see now. the comment needs to be updated.
Shouldn't this be a call to res_CreateIoPlaceholder()?
placeholder is already created in resTree_GetResource

Sorry, Shouldn't this be calling CreateEntry() and then attaching an Input resource to it using res_CreateIoPlaceholder() and res_ConvertPlaceholderToInput()?

The use of resTree_GetResource() seems a little indirect.
check again in the new patchset.
This part needs to be deleted.
No. This should not be called if there's already a resource at that path. So, it shouldn't be replacing something that's already at that path.

The only thing being replaced is a placeholder with the actual ioresource. Which isn't actually a replacement, it's a conversion. In that sense the placeholder isn't a thing, it's just holding the place until this resTree_CreateInput is invoked.

Ah, I see. I thought we were using a find function to see if something exists, and if it's a placeholder or namespace, convert it using a convert function.  But the create function can also convert.  It's a tricky behaviour, so I don't like it, but it should work, and the new comment makes it clearer, although, a Placeholder is a Resource, so the comment "Should not be called if there's already a resource at that path." isn't correct.
I'll modify the comment further to make it more correct.
This part needs to be deleted.

Created ticket for suggested improvement.

Clarified a documentation.
Ready for review again.

commits.commitMessage:
Allow to push data coming from a local file

    In order to be able to load data from a file into a specific
    resource, the option --file is added to dhub push command.
    The related file have to be formated as JSON.

Resolves: LE-15347
Change-Id: I7cc9b00685394d2a3f8150e833ec246fb35e9f41
Signed-off-by: olivier gallais <OGallais@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: Allow to push data coming from a local file

comments.message:
Since this is only used in the PushFile() function, it should be moved there.

(I can't see a reason for it to be static either. It could just be on the stack.)
This is already checked in the calling function.
extra space at end of line
Extra space at end of line. Please consider configuring your editor to automatically remove those, so this does not keep coming up in reviews.
What's the reason for not using le_fs() on WP7x platforms?

le_fs() does not support atomic operations, last time I checked.  Was that fixed? If not, it is not a robust choice because power loss or crash in the middle of an operation will result in lost files.

However, if only reading is being done, then it doesn't matter.

There is API le_atomFile_*() that supports atomic operations.
But yeah, it's not particularly important for this use case.

Need a name-spacing prefix like 'fileUtils_' on all identifiers visible outside the module.
See https://docs.legato.io/latest/ccodingStdsFormat.html#codingFormatNamingPrefixes

Hi Olivier,

Please see comments inserted.
Also, is there any reason why string type is not supported when reading from a file?

Thanks,
Ian
All other push routines are located in adminService.c (i.e. functions like admin_PushSomething()). Any particular reason to break this consistency and place PushFile here?

I think the difference here is that the push functions of the datahub accept data directly from memory.  This change to get the data from a file is only part of the dhub application, not the datahub itself.

If there is use case other than this one, where applications need the datahub to retrieve data from a file, then we might consider creating functions on the APIs for it.  Otherwise, I think this belongs here, in the app which is choosing to load the data from a file to the DH.
Now when this is just a very simple wrapper around le_fs, does this deserve to be a separate component? Can le_fs_*() be just called directly from PushFile()?
I agree.  This function should at least be moved into adminTool/tool.c.  I don't think this is significant enough to justify a separate component
Open mode should be read only (LE_FS_RDONLY)
It could be really handy to take input from stdin sometimes.  A common pattern for that is to pass '-' as the file name when you want to read from standard input.
I think that could easily be added as a future enhancement if needed.
I find these backwards comparisons a pain to read. But more important, this is not the style used in the rest of the file.
An 'else if' here would reduce nesting and better match the rest of the function.
This is not really a format. I think something like "TakeInputFromFile" or "ReadFromFile" would be a better name.

commits.commitMessage:
Update snapshot API for Octave compatibility

 - Add support for Octave CBOR-based format to snapshot API (octaveFormatter)
 - Only clear node's newness flag at the end of snapshot (add a resource flag)
 - Track resource's JSON example modification (add a resource flag)
 - Make some resource tree function public for Octave formatter use
 - Do not close read end of pipe from dataHub
 - Minor improvements in error handling

Resolves: LE-14969
Change-Id: Ibee72c8c64ce760cfb09998d87c1cea2038062dc
(cherry picked from commit 5d169d2ad724676642b5d16709522e5fe45a4978)
Signed-off-by: imorrison <imorrison@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: Update snapshot API for Octave compatibility

comments.message: Please provide a more detailed commit message.
I'm not certain about the need for this flag, but I'll come back to it after I've reviewed the formatter code.

The aim is to be able to keep nodes marked as new for the whole snapshot duration as Octave formatter process new and modified nodes in 2 different passes when not sending the full tree (new 1st, modified 2nd).
Thus, it was needed to make sure only the new flag of nodes that were processed is removed (to ensure well processing all nodes)
Does the JSON example actually change dynamically?  I thought it would generally just be set when a resource is created and then not modified.
Usually it doesn't, but the API allows it so we prefer to track it in order to only report it if it did change
Please wrap this line to keep it at or below 100 characters.
This doesn't seem to be referenced in the snapshot code.
This is directly passed to the Octave formatter and used there. should it be referenced after the custom flag?
Yes, the intention was that flags which are specific to individual formatters would use SNAPSHOT_FLAG_CUSTOM or greater.  That way we don't have to modify the .api file when a new formatter is added.
Strictly speaking this shouldn't be necessary, since LE_DEBUG() will already be removed by the preprocessor if LE_DEBUG_ENABLED is not defined.

I had to add this because of a build error in the Octave WP77 build:
jsonFormatter.c:703:50: error: ‘stepNames’ undeclared (first use in this function);
Right... on the HL78 we actually have the KConfig setting selected so that debug-level messages are preprocessed out entirely by default, which wouldn't be the case on Linux.

Hi Andrew,
Thanks for the review.  Please see my replies
Ian
Yes, this is true, needs to be changed to ClearNewness()

comments.message:
This word isn't needed.

But should explain how this is different from le_mem_Alloc().
do not return le_no_memory for delete.

Perhaps we should merge all the resource pools into one? Or, at least allow placeholders allocated from the I/O point pool if they are created under /app/X/ or from the observation pool if they are created under /obs.

Using a separate pool for placeholder seem to be a memory saving measure,
I think we can try to allocate a placeholder and if failed just use a regular resource.

Yes, I initially did it that way with memory savings in mind, but I see now that it doesn't really save memory, but rather eats a bunch of extra memory.  In the normal case, the administrator would set settings on resources that will actually be used.  So, generally, they'd be Observations, Inputs or Outputs. Placeholders are only needed when the settings are set by the Administrator app before the Input, Output, or Observation is created, or to retain settings after the Input, Output or Observation is deleted, temporarily, due to an app restart, for example. So, when all settings have been set and all Inputs, Outputs and Observations have been created, there should be no Placeholders in the system, and the Placeholder Pool is just taking up space.

Interesting, I already have a code that uses resources for placeholder, I'll put that up now and look at removing the placeholderpool altogether. though we can also just reduce the size to a very small value.

Hi Jen,
Please check resTree_DeleteIO and see what you think now.

Hi everyone, 
Can I get more opinions on this issue?
Please check the latest changes.

The idea was to replace

 GoToEntry(baseNamespace, path, doCreate)

with

 FindEntry(baseNamespace, path)
and
 CreateEntry(baseNamespace, path)

Then this code (and other function bodies that use GoToEntry()) should be split into 2 (more straightforward) paths, based on the return value from FindEntry().

I don't think the original idea of GoToEntry with doCreate as an argument is so bath though.
when I look at the implementation of GoToEntry, doCreate only plays a role at a certain point, so separating it to two functions would mean we have two function with large overlaps, this can be cause for future divergence and hence bugs.

Having a distinct FindEntry means that we can rely on a NULL return indicating that it simply didn't find the entry, and a distinct CreateEntry means that we can always interpret a NULL return from that as indicating an allocation failure.  There is then no ambiguity about what the returned value means.  The only other way to avoid that ambiguity would be to also pass back some sort of clarifying return code to differentiate the cases.

I'll do the FindEntry and CreateEntry,
but need another layer to check the path, today the NULL returned from GoToEntry can also mean that the path was malformed.

This is an interesting case. I don't think the sensor app should be told that its sample was rejected just because one down-stream observation failed to perform a transformation of the data. The data sample was still accepted as the current value of the input resource, and could have been delivered all the way to the Cloud Interface via some other path. ...Besides, there's nothing the sensor app can do about it.
Will change the obs_ApplyTransform so it never returns NULL. That will eliminate this case.
from an ORP pov we would be happy to use this info to slowdown the flux by informing the peer that the system is struggling by kicking the hardware flow control of the UART.

Hmm...  This code doesn't look right. It is returning "could not set default value due to type or unit mismatch" AFTER it has already set the default value.

I think there is a misunderstanding regarding the pre-existing code. The message is a warning, not an error. The default value is still set. It just has no effect on the current value of the resource because the type doesn't match.

I think the reason it is accepted (which should probably be documented here to avoid future confusion) is that the resource could later be replaced with another one with a type that matches the default value.
In a discussion with the team it was proposed to first check of the dataType is acceptable and if not, return with LE_BAD_PARAMETER instead of first setting them on the resource and then checking.

Hi Moe,

Please see comments inline

Thanks,
Ian
In many places you've added a colon after @return.  Does that generate proper Doxygen output?
not good with writing for Doxygen, that's out of a bad habit, I'll search and remove them.
Return code here should be LE_BAD_PARAMETER, per description above
Although this works, it is not really correct to set this flag without first testing ret
I would put this clean up code under the last `if (ret != LE_OK)`

If the return value here is not LE_OK, such as LE_BAD_PARAMETER, shouldn't we delete the sample which was created?  Otherwise, we can leak memory.
Same question/comment for the admin_Set*Override functions below
strangely, releasing the dataSample in case of error seems to have been done in SetOverride!

Recommend imposing a sanity limit on i:
    while (path[i] != '\0' && i < HUB_MAX_RESOURCE_PATH_BYTES)
I believe double slashes should be considered invalid as well

would be a change in behaviour though,
we've been accepting them so far.
In a discussion with the team it was suggested to keep the current behaviour specially since that change would be out of the scope of this commit.
could save a second call by using a stack variable here...
Remove or change to LE_DEBUG.  Same for following log statements.
Looking at the change, maybe this should default to true, and only be set to false for the few cases that need it.
resTree_Push() will free the sample for some errors and not for others.  I recommend that resTree_Push() should not free anything.  The sample should be freed by the caller which created it.
As per our discussion, freeing the sample is done but downstream code at the first case of failure.

I am surprised we allowed this.  It looks like this can cause 2 resources with excessively long names to be truncated to the same thing.
Also, how does the client know about the truncation?
Maybe we need another ticket to look at this.

Interesting catch,
what everyone else thinks?
Will change to return with NULL in that case instead of truncating.
Please use a blank line between variable declarations and the first instruction
Looks like we need to release entryRef in the event of these failures
Looks like we need to release entryRef in the event of these failures
Looks like we need to release entryRef in the event of these failures
Now that this function returns an error, the call to le_mem_Release(dataSample) should probably be made by the caller.  Otherwise, the sample is freed for some errors and not for others.
As per our discussion dataSample is released at the first place where an error happens.
Should we cache the result code and continue pushing to the entire list?

If we cache and continue pushing, then it's preserving the current behavior.
Though in that case, the return code would be a little weird, meaning not getting LE_OK doesn't mean it's failed, it could mean it's partially succeeded in updating the value.

We could add a new return code to alleviate this, LE_OK for when sample was pushed to all destinations successfully, and some other error if it was successfully pushed for some but there was an error on some others.

Hi Everyone, 
Can I get a couple of more opinions on this behavior ?

I think we should stick to the existing behaviour as much as possible (i.e. cache and continue).  It should be documented that LE_NO_MEMORY means that at least some of the destinations didn't receive the update, so they might have a gap in their data.  Also maybe log a warning indicating which destination didn't receive an update due to the allocation failure.
I agree. I think the only challenge is that res_Push may return different values for different list items, say LE_BAD_PARAMETER for one and LE_NO_MEMORY for another.

In that case, I would think it's OK to return LE_BAD_PARAMETER, if that is the actual error for one of the samples.

There is a second problem here as well:  We could see more than one failure with different result codes - e.g. res_Push could return LE_OK, then LE_BAD_PARAMETER, then LE_NO_MEMORY.  In cases like this, we should return the most severe failure, namely LE_NO_MEMORY.

Hi Moe,

Looks good.  There is one unresolved discussion in resource.c.  I think you, Andrew, and I were in agreement on what the behavior should be however, I have added one more case to consider.

Thanks,
Ian

Hi Moe,
Looks good to me now.
Thanks,
Ian
Thanks, Moe. Sorry it took so long to get around to reviewing this.

Hi Jen, Moe,
Please see my reply in the comments.
Thanks,
Ian

Hi All,
Please see my reply to Jen's last comment in resource.c
Thanks,
Ian
The old behaviour is to truncate the name and continue. Do we need to change that for some reason?

Yes.
The old behavior risked creating too resources with the same name even though the user gave different names
I would expect that the truncation would never actually occur if the path was properly validated, so this could just abort (LE_ASSERT_OK) and thereby avoid the added complexity of returning NULL.
It assumes the path is valid.
It should never be called when the entry already exists.  It should always return a new Namespace entry.
I don't where that requirement comes from

Since we have added FindEntry(), people should be calling that first and only calling CreateEntry() when it wants to create an entry. It is not called FindOrCreateEntry().

It's a fact that whenever it creates an entry, it always creates a Namespace entry.
I would prefer to see less duplicated code. Maybe the old GoToEntry() function could be used as a sub-function of FindEntry() and CreateEntry()?

Also, if CreateEntry() fails to allocate the memory for the last node in a path (after creating some parent, grandparent, etc. namespaces along the way), it doesn't look like those get cleaned up before returning.
I wonder if the path checking should be done in the API function implementations? So, validate the inputs at the interface to the clients, then assume it's good in internal functions.

I also think sanitizing user import right at the point that it's received is a better idea.
I'll look into it and see if we can fit it into this commit or becomes too much.
So, "Done" must mean that you looked into it and decided it was too much for this commit. Is that right?
Yeah I prefer to not do it as part of this patch.

I don't know if this helps, but note that a pre-existing Namespace doesn't really need to be deleted, since a Namespace is just an entry without a resource object. Instead, it could be converted into a placeholder resource.
will reuse entry if failed to allocate place holder.
The idea was to try to simplify this function by getting rid of the `createdEntry` variable.
The function prototype is changed in this case. So it has to report more.

The cyclomatic complexity of this function has gone from 3 (in the base) with 1 level of nesting to a cyclomatic complexity of 8 with 5 levels of nesting, and the length has more than tripled. That's what's bothering me. But, it's probably okay, I guess. I can see why the complexity is forced to increase because of the fact that res_CreatePlaceholder() takes an entryRef, which we may or may not yet have. But I find myself looking for ways to refactor to simplify.

The basic logic can be described as "If there's already a resource, return it. Otherwise, create a placeholder and return that." So, it seems simple on the surface. Of course, the memory reference counts have to be managed very carefully, so that adds more complexity. It just feels like this is getting tricky enough that it will come back to bite us someday during future maintenance work.

Perhaps returning directly from the error locations and doing a small amount of code duplication could pay off in a reduction in overall complexity?

(Also, if the path validation is moved to the API calls, then we can go back to just returning NULL on error.)
Keeping return locations to a minimum and preferably to one is one of our guidelines in legato as far as I know. I'm not sure if it's official or something we just prefer within our own team though.
It should have less indentation with the new ReplaceWithPlaceholder function.
This does not look like an improvement. This function is much more complex that it was with GoToEntry().

The complexity doesn't really come from changing GoToEntry to FindEntry and CreateEntry, it's coming from "Creating a new Input resource if nothing exists at that path." The previous implementation has one "GoToEntry" call which has to be turned into two calls in the fail safe implementation. 

The implementation has also become more complex because of the fact that for a particular type of resource there is two levels of resource allocation, any of which could fail and a failure in the second allocation requires cleanup of the first. This requirement did not exist in the previous implementation resulting in a simpler code.
Maybe it should be split into functions like resTree_CreateInput() and resTree_ReplaceWithInput()? The calling function already knows if it exists or not and what type of entry it is.
alowing early return would reduce the nesting
our team has generally gravitated toward having only a single exit point and that's why I've written these function the way the are.

Yes, this is one of the few points where I disagree with MISRA, and this function is a great example of where I would do things differently than MISRA. If used carefully, returning from multiple points can greatly simplify code, and thereby reduce the maintenance cost and defect count.  The key is to keep it obvious where the returns are happening and think about whether someone adding new code to this function would be likely to accidentally create a defect because of the additional return point(s). Even then, a comment can serve as a warning sign to prevent later adventurers in this part of the code from falling into the pitfall.

By the way, even MISRA has downgraded this from Standard to Advisory.
"Done" here seems to mean "decided to leave it as it is." That's not how I would typically interpret "Done." ;)
lol. I actually meant to use ACK but used Done accidentally. With the new function, then indentation level should be fine though.

It's just a bit awkward to follow the logic.  Seems like things could be structured more cleanly. In particular, the `ret = LE_NO_MEMORY` is separate from the code that checks the return from CreateEntry().  It seems like it would work, though, I think.  I'll add some more specific comments to the newer changeset.

Could this be replaced with a single call to a (new) function res_ConvertToPlaceholder(entryRef) that converts the entry into a placeholder?

I think the Placeholder Pool should be eliminated to save RAM.

I'll do the res_ConvertToPlaceholder(entryRef) to make it more straightforward.
but I don't think we should delete the placeholder pool. as part of this change.
specially if the intention is to save RAM. We'll need to compensate for the deleted place holder by increasing the size of resource pool which actually consume more memory per object.
Sure. I'm good with leaving the removal of the Placeholder Pool until a later change.
I think this needs to be replaced with an allocation from one of the other pools (I/O Point Pool or Observation Pool), depending on the first node in the path (is it under /app or /obs?)

I don't think removing the placeholder pool as part of this change is a good idea. It's already become a pretty big and potentially risky commit. I could argue it's not completely within the scope of this commit either.

What I've done though is changing IoDelete function to reuse the resource object as a placeholder instead so we don't have to return le_no_memory from a delete function. That's the only that really needs to go out this time because we're putting all API changes into this commit. further optimizations can be done later.
Both of these cases do the same thing.

No. if we haven't seen any error yet, (res == LE_OK), then we'll cache whatever pushRes (result of latest push) is. If we have seen an error, but now we saw a "no memory" error, we'll overwrite previous error with the no memory error because it's more important to report this.

I mean, it literally does the same thing:
 res = pushRes;

(The only difference is that one is indented with 3 spaces instead of 4)

I think I'd like to see some more comments in here too. The reasoning that you gave for this logic is really not obvious from the code alone.

This wasn't addressed. I think a comment explaining the algorithm is required, at least.

In particular, I'm wondering why other error codes are just ignored.
yeah I forgot this. Other errors are deemed to have less priority compared with le_no_memory.

I'm still not convinced that this is the correct way to solve this problem. The Data Hub was designed around a fire-and-forget, publish-subscribe architecture. The publisher shouldn't care if anyone is listening. The sensor did its job. It took the sample and pushed it to the Data Hub. If an error occurred after that, it should be escalated to someone who can actually do something about it. It is not the sensor's responsibility to solve the Data Hub's memory problems.

But sensor aren't the only clients of datahub,
there are clients like cloudInterface storing device configuration in datahub trees, I assume that kind of client would care about the push result.
Even ORP passes a return code when handling an AT command. So an ORP Push AT command would have a return code regardless and it's much more clear if that return code matched what exactly happened in the datahub rather than always reporting a success like it does today.

Types of client, like sensors, that do not care can just ignore the return value.

The Cloud Interface (or whatever the Administrator app is) needs to know if memory allocation failed for anyone, even if it wasn't their own request that failed.  So, there needs to be a mechanism to receive fault reports from the Data Hub (that cannot fail because of an out-of-memory condition).

For AT commands, it's a request-response interaction, not a publish-subscribe interaction. So, that seems like it needs a different mechanism than data sample pushes.

Hi Jen,

That's a good point; the CI should know about memory exhaustion as it is more or less the monitor of system health in Octave.  I can see that these changes will allow the Datahub, and the system, to continue running in a "wounded" state.  This is bad if no action is taken.

It seems to make sense to create a mechanism for catching this, such as by notifying the CI.  I would prefer to do it as a separate feature, though, and limit the scope of the change to only avoiding the aborts.  Shall we open a separate ticket?

I think that the relationship between a client who pushed data, and an observer who receives it is still intact - ie. publisher-consumer.  These return values only indicate that the publish  operation itself is failing.  It doesn't say anything about what happens if the data is successfully published.

Thanks,
Ian

Isn't the caller pushing the data in free to ignore the return code? Not having any indication removes even the option... to me returning errors is always a good thing. I'm i.n favour or the LE_FAULT - perhaps it's too generic could be an opportunity to be more specific what went wrong.

I would also allow the calling application decide whether to cache any errors / information. It would publish these through the datahub in the normal fashion. Adding more data to node in DH at these memory constrained times is probably not best. Let the application decide.

There are 2 things that are bothering me about this:

1. The addition of a return code increases the complexity of the API, so I want to be convinced that there is significant value added by that extra complexity.

2. It's possible that a pushed value may be successfully stored and even pushed much of the way through the Data Hub's chain of resources that care, but at some stage, a memory allocation may fail and prevent the distribution of the sample to one consumer. That then gets reported as a failure.  But, if the failure of memory allocation happens after it gets passed out of the Data Hub to another app, the distribution of the sample has still effectively failed and is not reported all the way back to the publisher. So, the OK return code doesn't necessarily mean that it's OK, and therefore it adds no value.

Hi Jen,

When you say:  "But, if the failure of memory allocation happens after it gets passed out of the Data Hub to another app ...",  this is on the consumer side of the exchange, is it not?  If it is on the consumer side, then how does this differ from the situation we have now?

Thanks,
Ian

It doesn't differ from the situation we have now. That's part of my point. I don't think we should change the API like this. We should just stop the crashing for now, and design in a new fault management system that actually does what we need as a separate change.

Hi All,

Jen and I had a conversation about this offline and I agree with what he is saying, particularly when it comes to memory exhaustion.  We need to avoid the aborts but returning LE_NO_MEMORY is of little value.  If the aborts are removed, there needs to be a mechanism for detecting and dealing with memory exhaustion, and this can't come from just any random client.

Rather than disrupting the API now, I think we can leave it as-is until we have agreed on a method for handling the no memory problem.  We can do that under a separate ticket.  If an API change really is needed, at least it can happen all at once.

OK?
So, when you say, "leave it as-is", you mean, remove the API changes from this change set (but keeping the abort-prevention code internal to the Data Hub) right?

"The Data Hub was designed around a fire-and-forget, publish-subscribe architecture."
Data hub was designed with some "requirements", but now the product using it is dealing with important samples and the client must know if there is an issue processing the samples to be sure to not drop it on he floor.

so I value the addition of the return codes.

I don't want to have to invent another side channel to give the information to the client that there is an issue and it should not drop samples.

Thanks for that feedback, Julien.

I agree that we need some way of indicating back-pressure over ORP (and otherwise) for applications that need guaranteed end-to-end delivery. The Data Hub could be augmented to support that feature, but it really isn't how the Data Hub was designed. Can we discuss design options for that end-to-end feature and add that as a separate change?
will make clear in api documentation that LE_OK does not provide end-to-end guarantee and also that there is a chance sample will be lost due to power outage.

Since CreateEntry() is an internal function that should never be called unless FindEntry() has already been called to confirm that the entry doesn't yet exist, we might as well LE_FATAL if the node already exists so that a NULL return value from CreateEntry() always means that a memory allocation failed.

Also, if we LE_FATAL at line 363 when ((childPtr != NULL) && (*terminatorPtr == '\0')), then we don't need to do this FindEntry() call. (*terminatorPtr == '\0') is how we know entryName is the last node name in the path.
This doesn't seem like it will loop over the right set of nodes. E.g., if two entries got added, then firstNewEntry will not be the currentEntry and none will get cleaned up.

Hmm...  Seems like we could just unconditionally change the entry type to PLACEHOLDER. That is, always just reuse the pool block. That is much simpler code and can never fail.  Maybe we want to leave that for now, though, until the Placeholder Pool is eliminated?
yeah, testing this patch is already a big challenge. would prefer to keep it limited in this patch and then do a simple patch later.
This isn't needed, because it's already initialized to this value.
This seems like it should be in an else case to the if statement beginning on line 751.
Patch test passed - see LETEST-6154 & Quan's +1 above

commits.commitMessage:
Add io and query APIs to set client app namespace

    In order to fix issue where datahub resource created over RPC use
    rpcProxy namespace in place of the calling application name, add new
    APIs to io and query so namespace can be set by client application.

Resolves: LE-15082
Change-Id: I196523e265a9193a25c51a1c855feff17d9b6170
commits.subject: Add io and query APIs to set client app namespace

comments.message: Is this true?  One shouldn't be _required_ to set the namespace (it should default to the app name in the same way it does now).

I thought about making the app name the default namespace, but that'll give the same problem we have before, a datahub client over rpcproxy may connect and expect it's own name to be the namespace only to be surprised when the namespace is set to rpc proxy.

It should be illegal to set the namespace to something other than the app name on Linux. The namespacing is not just for convenience (if anything, it's inconvenient). It is a security feature.

Ideally, the RPC proxy should actually run as several apps (perhaps sharing a stack where RAM limitations require it). Each of those apps would have the same name as the remote app it is proxying for, so that the DataHub can't tell the difference whether the client app is running locally or remotely through a proxy. I get that there are some significant obstacles to achieving this ideal on our current Legato/FreeRTOS. Regardless, we should be striving to keep this complexity out of the app code (including the DataHub) and the inter-app APIs.

The le_msg and le_appInfo APIs are used to get the app name from the Service Directory and Supervisor. For FreeRTOS support, we should add a feature that allows the RPC Proxy to set the app name for specific IPC sessions, such that calls to `le_msg_GetClientProcessId()` and `le_appInfo_GetName()` for those sessions ultimately returns the name specified by the RPC Proxy. (No other apps should be allowed to use that feature, though.) To make this simpler, perhaps we could add a single le_msg call like `le_msg_GetAppName(sessionRef)` that returns the name of the app on the other end of an IPC session connection, so that we don't have create fake PIDs for the RPC proxy.
It should still default to the old behaviour if no namespace is explicitly provided.
see my comment on the .api file.
Check the lifetime of this.  You might need to le_mem_AddRef() and later le_mem_Release() to ensure the stored session context pointer stays valid.

hmmm,
the old code didn't do le_mem_AddRef for this purpose. so either they've checked or there was a bug,
I can double check.
It doesn't seem like this value is ever released
Is there a define for the maximum app name length somewhere?  This should be the same for compatibility with the existing names.
I think there is an LE_LIMIT define for app names.

Yes, the dataHub uses le_limit.api:
LE_LIMIT_APP_NAME_LEN  (== 47)
Probably better to use the same, no?
See previous comments about preserving existing behaviour by default.
See previous comment about name length.
Is this still used?  I thought we were going to use a value from le_limit.api.
this is a mistake, it should look like the one in io_lite.api

This always returns LE_OK, so might as well remove the return code.
...unless you plan to add permissions checks somehow. Although, a failed permission check  should probably return something like LE_NOT_PERMITTED.

If you're storing this somewhere else, should do an AddRef.  And do Release on the previous value.  Otherwise there's a risk of issues if the entry is released.

Alternatively -- just store the namespace name and do "getEntry" each time instead of storing a pointer to the node.
Yes, be extra careful here, because there's potential for a memory leak or a use-after-release. This is one of the more tricky aspects of the current Data Hub design, unfortunately.
I don't see any permissions checks. Please don't just skip that.

You need to register a disconnect handler, and release this pointer on disconnect.

Irrelevant for now, but will created a memory leak if this is ever used on Linux.

Either that or ASSERT(!LE_CONFIG_LINUX) here and put a comment.
I'll use ASSERT(!LE_CONFIG_LINUX) and put a comment.
This is never actually used. It's better not to list fault codes that aren't used, because clients will waste time checking for those codes.

Recommend

    #if LE_CONFIG_LINUX
        LE_FATAL("Not permitted on Linux!");
    #endif

or some variation thereof.

Patch Set 4:

(3 comments)

As follow up to the discussion in the code review, the deletion logic is okay as-is, because only leaf notes in the form of I/O resources or observations can be deleted explicitly.  Branch nodes are only removed if they have no more children.

For this reason, there will never be an issue with a node being deleted and recreated within a snapshot window causing the loss of deletion information about children.  Parent nodes are reference counted by their children, and except for the top root node, removing all children will trigger the removal of the parent.

commits.commitMessage:
Implement tracking of deleted items in snapshot API

Now snapshot requests can include information on resource tree nodes
deleted since the last flush of the tree.  As part of this, formatters
can request multiple sequential scans of the resource tree filtered by
node state as part of a snapshot operation.  As an example, this allows
the existing nodes to be considered in one pass, and the deleted nodes
to be considered in another.

Each node now has three states indicating its lifetime:
 * "New," indicating it has never been captured by a previous snapshot.
 * "Deleted," indicating the node has been deleted.  Deleted nodes are
   only provided if deletion tracking is turned on.
 * "Normal," indicating the node is in the regular portion of its
   existence.

A pair of periodically added and removed resources have been added to
the actuator demo program to assist with testing.

Resolves: LE-14968
Change-Id: I979ad3d83ae3000d4c820a6948ae2a651e4bbb18
commits.subject: Implement tracking of deleted items in snapshot API

comments.message: Assert that child list is empty as well.
Don't need this check due to the assertions in SetDeleted
I realized it doesn't make sense remove this, since resTree_IsDeleted() may be called on nodes of any type, but only namespace nodes can have the flag set.

That was the point -- RES_FLAG_DELETED will never be set if resEntry is not a namespace, so there's no need to specifically check if it's a namespace.

Minor point though.

There is, because the flags are stored in the same location as the pointer to the associated resource (union fields).  If it is a namespace, there is no associated resource and the local flags are used.  If it is not, then the flags are actually located in the resource that the pointer refers to.  For this reason we still have to check the type to make sure that the flags field is going to be valid.

commits.commitMessage:
Add a wrapper script for running DH in GDB

This sets up the environment and runs the Data Hub in GDB, within a
tmux session which can be attached to.  Some initial data is also
populated in the Data Hub.  The startup takes a few seconds to
complete.  Use "make stop" to terminate the environment.  The GDB
session will still need to be closed manually.

Resolves: LE-14968

commits.commitMessage:
Introduce resource tree snapshot feature to the Query API

This feature provides a "TakeSnapshot" API function which traverses all
or part of the Data Hub resource tree and encodes the results using
formatter plugins.  Various parameters control which information is
returned and how it is formatted.

The full implementation is a pair of interlocked state machines, one in
the snapshot core and one in the formatter plugin.  The snapshot code
walks through the resource tree in a depth-first traversal, and for
each node the formatter generates output and writes it to the output
stream file descriptor.  All of the steps take advantage of the Legato
event loop to maintain sequencing and to allow flow control on the
output stream.

This initial commit introduces the snapshot core code, but does not
include any formatters.  It also does not yet support deletion tracking
of resource tree nodes.

Resolves: LE-13032
Change-Id: I2ec9993b942c9f37c98dfbcaf7e8aa1c6343b8ad
commits.subject: Introduce resource tree snapshot feature to the Query API

comments.message: I'm thinking I probably want to do this a little differently.  On Linux I think it should use pipe() or pipe2(), and on RTOS a platform-specific pipe rather than a FIFO.
Change name to indicate beginning of custom values.
Check and change to bitmask type?
Check if entry is a resource before accessing union member?
It will actually always be a namespace (deleted items are always converted to the namespace type), but either way the value should be 0 or NULL.

Technically behaviour is undefined if you read from a different union member than was written to.  

This could be important in practice for platforms with 64-bit pointers, as writing 0 to flags could leave some bits of resourcePtr non-zero.
Note: not C++, so I think this is technically not necessary.
Well, compilation with GCC for localhost fails without it.
Why are these defined with these specific values and not say 0x01 and 0x02, for example?

I have an idea for a numeric value that might reside in the lower part of the flags.  I'm not sure if I'll ultimately use it, but arranging them this way means that I can just mask the bits to recover that value without doing any shifting.

commits.commitMessage:
Add Data Hub to basic HL78 MCU system

Create a light version of io.api with reduced buffer sizes to
accomodate the MCU.  Use a symlink to select the desired flavour.

Resolves: LE-14520
Change-Id: I79f275a71bcd3748b05964b06a3ae66fee6e0709
commits.subject: Add Data Hub to basic HL78 MCU system

commits.commitMessage:
Changes to support Data Hub on ALT1250 MCU

 * Fix various GCC warnings.
 * Transition to static memory pools and configurable memory allocation
   behaviour.
 * Conditionally compile Linux and file system features.
 * Conditionally disable the admin tool.

Resolves: LE-12588 LE-13030
Change-Id: I09a5f0a68d8179cc5aef9f4f098ad6e4e6025ee3
commits.subject: Changes to support Data Hub on ALT1250 MCU

comments.message: How did you come to choose a value of 2?
It seemed a reasonable default for the number of things that would be listening for changes to the resource tree.

I find this a little confusing because you are re-using the laterStringPool reference variable.  I think it would be clearer if you declared a second le_mem_PoolRef_t variable to hold the results of the first CreateReducedPool call.
It's just a temporary variable.  There is no need to reference it again after it has been passed to the next pool creation.
So why is this pool set to 10, while some of the previous pool sizes are set to 5?   Is there a rhyme and a reason to this?

They are all based on rough estimates of the reasonable number of each type of object for a low-memory system.  On Linux the default behaviour allows the pools to grow dynamically so this won't be a limitation.  On both Linux and RTOS the sizes can be overridden in the .cdef file if the defaults aren't sufficient.
Don't make this change.  We will have to locally make this change in the short term until we resolve it properly.
You're right.  I probably got a little carried away with copying and pasting.  It shouldn't affect anything, though.  I can follow up later with another patch (created LE-13330).

On a non-Linux system that has a file system, the backup files will never get cleaned up.
Should be made to generate an error at build time in that case.

commits.commitMessage:
Bring Legato project up to date with latest Data Hub

These are all non-breaking changes. That is, all existing clients should continue to work after a re-build.

- The resource naming conventions in the io.api were out of date wrt what people are actually doing. Updated that.
- psensor component was using malloc() and free(). Converted to a memory pool.
- Added a psensor_CreateJSON() that takes a JSON example string instead of a data type, but otherwise functions in exactly the same way as the generic psensor_Create() function.
- Made it possible to have all the resources of a periodic sensor appear directly under the app name in the data hub.
- Trigger a first sample immediately upon enabling when a period is configured, rather than waiting until the first timer expiry before triggering the first sample.
- Moved the observation buffer backup directory on embedded targets from /data to /home/root to make this feature work again on newer Sierra Wireless WP modules.
- Added a second pool for smaller string data samples so we don't have to allocate 50KB for every little string.

Resolves: LE-13114
Change-Id: Ic63ddd7b657594d114844e92fa7346f185f072e9
commits.subject: Bring Legato project up to date with latest Data Hub
